There are problems in 
org.eclipse.help.ui.internal.browser.embedded.EmbeddedBrowserAdapter.close() 
method implementation:

		Display defaultDisplay = Display.getDefault();
		if (defaultDisplay == Display.getCurrent()) {
			uiClose();
		} else {
			defaultDisplay.syncExec(new Runnable() {
				public void run() {
					uiClose();
				}
			});
		}

The assumption that display exists is valid when this method is executed is 
inavlid.

Behavior during regular scenario (that I can reproduce):
Workbench window is shut down and disposes of shell and display.  This 
triggers disposal of help window.
Executing of EmbeddedBrowserAdapter.close() happens later on another thread 
that OSGi uses to shut down the org.eclipse.help plugin that keeps reference 
to EmbeddedBrowserAdapter from org.eclipse.help.ui.
The close() should do nothing, but it does and it creates a new display!  The 
Display.getDefault() creates a new one since original one got disposed by the 
workbench.  The uiClose() is invoked that does nothing and everything is fine.
The problem here is that Display was created without a need, and not disposed 
of.

Behavior during Jeff's scenario:
Workbench shutdown somehow failed (the first two stack traces - I think there 
are already bugs opened with these), and the display did not get disposed of.
The help.ui plug-in gets shuts down normally.
Shut down of help plug-in calls EmbeddedBrowserAdapter.close(), that this time 
realizes it is not on the UI thread, and executes syncExec(new Runnable() The  
new Runnable() fails, since the plug-in is in shut down state.

I think this needs to be fixed for 3.0.  I will think about a safe patch that 
will not disturb the code too much, and attach it later.

Opinions?
